    <a href="/reading/natural-breadcrumbs/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">← back to index</a>

    <h1>Compositional Game Theory</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Ghani, Hedges, Kupke, Forsberg · 2018 · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1603.04641"><img src="/reading/arxiv.webp" alt="arxiv" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/> arXiv:1603.04641</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/natural-breadcrumbs/staton-2025/">🍞 Staton 2025</a> (composition of programs). 5 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nash_equilibrium"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Nash equilibrium</a> is a <strong>compositional predicate</strong>: if each sub-game is in equilibrium given its context, the whole game is in equilibrium. Games compose like programs.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Open games -->
    <h3>Open games: games with interfaces</h3>
    <p>An <strong>open game</strong> has inputs (what the player observes) and outputs (what the player does), plus a coplay channel that carries consequences back. A function with a feedback wire. Wiring one game's output to the next game's input is sequential composition, same as for programs.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Single open game — right-pointing triangle: base left (input), tip right (output) -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 340 130" class="w-full max-w-sm" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Player triangle (right-pointing equilateral: base on left, tip on right) -->
        <polygon points="80,15 80,115 230,65" fill="#a1a1aa" fill-opacity="0.15" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
